about_the_job:
Oxford Policy Management (OPM) is delighted to announce that we are looking to hire a Monitoring, Evaluation, and Learning Consultant to join OPM’s Global Research and Evidence Practice within our Indonesia office.

The Research and Evidence Practice is a global team of MEL experts that seek to improve policies, programmes and service delivery in Low- and Middle-income Countries (LMICs) through strengthening the production and use of information and evidence and the systems and processes that support it, and so contribute to the reduction of poverty and disadvantage at scale. We do this in collaboration with our Sector Practices, which include Climate and Resilience, Governance, Social Protection, Health, Education, and Poverty. This approach offers high levels of methodological rigour in combination with deep thematic and contextual knowledge and expertise.

As a MEL consultant within Indonesia, you will work closely with our country and regional teams to support the winning and delivery of high-quality and impactful evaluation, MEL, and research projects across a broad range of sectors, in collaboration with colleagues from OPM’s Sectoral Practices with a primary focus on Indonesia. Our MEL work in Indonesia is focused on the implementation and management of several long-term projects and short-term technical assistance and MEL services for development partners such as the Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade (DFAT) and Foreign, Commonwealth and Development Office (FCDO).

Key Responsibilities

The consultant will have responsibilities in three areas. These are aligned with the OPM Indonesia strategy. In performing these responsibilities, the consultant will focus on opportunities in Indonesia and the Asia-Pacific region. The areas are:

Project Delivery
Apply MEL technical knowledge and facilitative methods to ongoing and new projects, particularly focused on the development and implementation of MEL frameworks;
Provide technical inputs into projects (including monitoring, evaluation and learning) at all stages of delivery, including inception, design, data collection, analysis, writing and reporting, and dissemination;
Lead small to medium-scale projects or a component/deliverable in a large project. The role will apply technical, programme management, people skills, and a focus on impact to deliver these projects successfully. This task may involve the provision of a coordination or leadership role for the project team and administrative support;
Ensure that outputs are delivered on time and in accordance with OPM MEL quality and report writing standards.

Business Development
Contribute to building the Research and Evidence Practice and the Indonesia MEL team’s portfolio of work by leading the bidding for new opportunities identified by the Indonesia country office and the regional MEL team;
Maintain and expand our network of national consultants, key experts and other organisations in the MEL field to work on programmes and projects and for potential collaborations in the future;
Build and maintain strong collaborative, consultative and collegial working relationships with clients, including DFAT and FCDO;
Track short and multi-year opportunities in line with OPM’s Strategy and pipeline targets;
Research and develop an understanding of the Indonesia MEL market.

Training and Technical Leadership
Join and actively engage with at least one of our Global Technical Communities of Practice, which provide the technical leadership for OPM in a range of MERL competencies, including: Evaluation, Impact Evaluation, Qualitative Research and Mixed Methods, Monitoring and Evaluation Systems, Evidence Use, Data Innovation, and Value for Money;
Take a proactive approach to on- and off-job personal and career development by working on projects across the MERL spectrum, keeping abreast of the latest methodological developments and taking opportunities to attend training events as appropriate; and
Develop strong and effective working relationships with OPM colleagues based in the practice, other practices, and other OPM offices.

Required Skills and Experience

Degree and post-graduate qualification in a relevant discipline (evaluation, international development, development economics, or other appropriate social science discipline);
Graduate-level training and advanced technical knowledge in monitoring and evaluation;
At least 5 years of experience delivering monitoring, evaluation or research projects, including some experience in leading or leading aspects of these projects;
Excellent written and oral communication skills, with high levels of attentiveness to diverse audiences
Ability to travel in the country and overseas for short-term assignments;
Willingness to work across different time zones

Preferred Skills and Experience

Familiarity with DFAT and FCDO Monitoring and Evaluation Standards, with associated relevant work experience;
Demonstrated experience in developing and delivering training on MEL;
Ability to work in English and Bahasa Indonesia;
Experience in Project Management, including the management of project teams.

The position is full-time and based in Indonesia, with the potential for some overseas travel. If you would like to work in a supportive environment that values collaboration, integrity, and empowerment, we would love to hear from you. OPM offer a competitive salary, a contribution pension scheme, and a generous holiday entitlement.
